segments.text: I was born here in El Paso.
All right, I'll begin with you.
Your family, where was your family from?
Well, my father was from Allende, Valle de Allende, Chihuahua.
Zacatecas, Zacatecas, capital of the state of Zacatecas.
My mother was, at the time, after the attack of Zacatecas from Machovilla, they captured a city, they had to leave.
So they came to Chihuahua and stayed with some of her relatives there.
My mother got a job working in the hospital.
I guess the way she tells me, it's sort of a nurse's aide.
Now, where in Chihuahua was this?
Yes, and that's where she met my father.
He was in the hospital recuperating from a bullet wound.
And after that, he left the hospital in here.
Well, how did he happen to get the bullet wound?
Yeah, I haven't got it clear, you know that?
My mother tells me that he was brought in with a wounded from Salaya.
Now, where or how he got it, I really don't know.
Oh, it must have been in, let's see, I think it was 14, 19, 14, 19, 13, somewhere in there.
I really don't know, because I was born in 1918, so I'm just assuming you know it, because...
They were married about two years before I was born.
Of course, I haven't got records on that.
Well, not records, but a few papers that he left.
after because sort of a political refugee.
Yeah, but the man that wanted to hang him was Murguia, General Murguia.
Now, I don't know who Murguia was.
See, that's one thing that I've never gotten clear.
So many politicians, they had their own people, powers, you might call them.
And according to my father, during the revolution, at one time they were friends, another time they were enemies, so I really don't know.
How did he happen to join Pancho Villa?
Did he ever talk about that?
No, no, only that according to his brothers, he was sort of the black sheep of the family, you know, the sheep of the family.
He was a rough one, in other words, because none of the brothers joined the revolution.
And they were always peaceful and all that.
Well, my father used to read that out.
And I guess that's how he left home and joined the forces.
I really don't know too much about it, but that's what I heard him talk about.
What had his father been, your grandfather?
Did they have their own land?
They had a little patch of land over in
I've never been that far myself.
The farthest I've been is Camargo.
That's as far as I've been into Mexico.
Well then, your father met your mother in Chihuahua City, and they married there?
No, right after he left the hospital.
Right after he left the hospital.
And then how did it happen that he had to leave?
This man wanted to hang him.
Well, it seemed like, you know, we as forces quit fighting or laid down our arms.
And then it seemed like he was already at peace.
And we came to Chihuahua, I guess, just for a visit or I don't know.
knew him very well, so he went riding around in his car.

And after Villa left and his men left, my father stayed back in Chihuahua, and then Murguia, he started rounding up all the villistas, or ex-villistas, whatever you want to call them, and hanging them, you see.
And somehow, I don't know what my father ever told Murguia or what Murguia had against my father, but he said, I want him dead or alive.
So he had to leave everything he had in Chihuahua.
He had a little store, and he had to leave everything.
According to my mother, this is what my mother told me, from Chihuahua they went to Aldama, disguised as the peasants, you know.
And there they got on a train, it was coming towards Juarez, and that's how they came right straight to El Paso.
And my father will, many, many years before you, went back to Mexico.
Oh, he did go back to Mexico?
Yeah, he did go back to Mexico.
It was always his dream of going back to Mexico.
But when he was here, the only reason he was here was because he was safe.
And what year did he go back to Mexico?
In fact, that was the reason my mother separated my father.
She didn't want to go back to Mexico.
And he insisted, and they insisted, and they broke up.
I mean, you know, I really don't know what happened, but he decided he wanted to go back to Mexico, so he got this.
So what year were you born?
And they crossed the border into the States?
So it would have been 1917 or 1918.
And how many children were there?
In my family, there was five.
Only the youngest, I'm the oldest, lived.
And what did your father do while he lived here in El Paso?
Well, he was an invalid then, because the bullet wound, you know, he was crippled for life.
He couldn't work for anybody, so he himself made his own living.
He'd done so many things, and we were in so many places.
We went out to California, picked fruit, and a lot of things like that.
You didn't just stay in El Paso.
You went to a lot of different places.
My father was sort of a wanderer.
He never could stay in one place.
And that was another reason my mother didn't want to follow him anymore.
I had a sister born in Colorado.
My brother was born in California.
We were just all over the country.
Crops and I don't know what else.
But he always worked for himself.
In other words, projects like a small restaurant or something like that.
What happened when he went back to Mexico?
Do you know where he went?
No, down here between Chihuahua and Juarez, in a place called Villamada.
And then he started getting sick, old and sick, you know, and so he had to leave the farm.
And then came the Juarez, and he was very sick the last time I saw him in Juarez, and he said, I'm going to leave Juarez, I'm going to go to a warmer climate, and I think I can do well.
So he was on his way to the southern part of Mexico, I don't know where, but he only made it to Chihuahua City,
And what year did he die?
And I wonder, was Alfredo born 50 this year?
Bertalicia was... Alfredo was one year old when he died.
Do you know about how old he was when he died?
So he was a fairly young man during the revolution.
What did I do with the picture?
Would you like to see it?
I would like to very much.
I don't know where it is.
While you're getting the picture, then I'll start with you.
Where were your mother and father from?
My mother was from Camaro, Chihuahua.
But my mother, she comes from her father and mother
And what were their names there?
And then they came, I think, when they had only three children, and then came to Camargo.
And my grandfather had a bakery.
That was a part of my mother.
But from my father, they were from the Chihuahua Chihuahua.
And what I hear, there were 13 of them.
Brothers and sisters and aunts and uncles and everything.
And they were kind of wealthy.
My grandfather had a... Well, it wasn't a farm.
It was more like a colonia for non-Muslims.
They used to call it Colonia Fernandez Leal.
But when this started, all the revolution and everything, they had about eight daughters, my grandfather, see?
And he was afraid that something would happen to them.
They brought here to El Paso their mattress and whatever luggage they could take and bring, see?
Because they were afraid of the ballistas.
And this is your mother and father?
This is my mother and the side of my father.
On the side of my father.
So they came over and it was about 1910 they were here.
Now, this is before he married your mother?
Did your father ever talk about what it was like?
Well, my father didn't used to talk too much.
But my aunt, the one that I had, , she was the one that got charge of the 13 ranches.
She was the only one left.
My father, well, he was an engineer.
And they didn't left him anything.
because he got married, and you know how they were.
This is after he got Del Paso.
But my aunt was the one...
Let me just... What I think I'll do is draw a picture so that I can get an idea of who's who.
All right, here's your mother, and her name was... Maria.
And when she... You wanted... Before she got married.
Now your mother and your mother's parents
We're from Italy, both of you.
Your grandmother on your mother's side.
And they came from Italy after they were married.
They had three children up there.
Did they ever say why they came from Italy?
Well, I think they never... You see, I was very small when my mother died.
I was about seven years old.
I couldn't remember exactly, but I know they came from Italy.
Now my mother and my father, they met here in El Paso.
Okay, they met in El Paso.
And I think it was that time of 1916, because my brother was born in 1917.
All right, how did your mother's family happen to come to El Paso?
Well, you see, they always used to come here to buy things.
Her clothes, winter clothes and summer clothes, because they were from El Paso.
Well, she knew my father in Chihuahua because she used to go with my mother over there.
And, in fact, my father wasn't even going with my mother, but with her cousin or something.
But when they came here to buy clothes or something,
He was here because he was here, my father was here since 1910.
So they met here and got married and they stayed here.
So her family though, her brothers and sisters didn't come here.
Who are they now, the brothers?
He has a drugstore in Camargo.
And they all live in Mexico.
And who were the other children in that family?
Well, there's that she was married to one of her brothers.
She's in another that I have there.
Now, what did her husband do?
And are there any others that are no longer living?
There was a, well, there's the, like, I'm the daughter, you know.
There's the Juan Camaro Severo Garza.
Yes, the son of my uncle.
And he has his son now taking care of the drug store.
So all this side of the family stayed in Mexico.
Did they have any trouble during the revolution, or did they just, they didn't?
Well, I don't know, but they used to tell me that one of Pancho Villa's men, because on my mother's side, they were kind of wealthy, you know.
that was killed by one of Pacho Villa's men.
And I don't know if it's true or not, but he never came back home.
Because he used to wear those, how do you call those?
One, they used to wear the man's on their tie.
And they used to say that one of the men's a poor shaman.
He told him that he wanted that jewelry.
And his uncle said, no, you come and get it.
So the other were just shot.
And that's what the end of it.
Now on your father's side, your father's parents, now your father's mother was?
And your mother's, your father's mother was?

Now, your father's father had a lot of land.
Porfirio Diaz came to my grandfather and asked him to lend him some money or something like that.
But my grandfather gave him money, so Porfirio Diaz gave him those ranches, the 13 ranches.
Do you know how many hectares it was?
It was 180 hectares or something like that.
We had a Max, we had Ed, and I can't find it.
And I have the Porfirio Diaz, everything that...
Yeah, I have Porfirio Diaz for mining.
I have things, but not for the ranches.
Because by Ed, she used to keep everything in a little box or something.
And she was very sick when she came down here, when she died, see?
So part was over there and she wallowed, part was over here.
We couldn't get the things that were in the wall.
But I have, if you want to see, yes, I have this.
And I have a, for a lot of things, not only, and I thought this was,
Now, what had your grandfather, Jose Perez, what kind of work did he do before he had the ranches?
Well, I think I can tell you.
citada ley y su reglamento de 26 de junio de 1892.
Could you just read the rest of it for me?
This is the one that you want.
I don't read it out loud that much.
This is the one you want.
This is the one you want.
You were asking about the hectares and everything, something like that.
But that writing, I'll tell you.
I think this was a brother of my grandfather, Celso Lugo.
And here's the signature of Porfirio Diaz.
And here's the signature of Porfirio Diaz.
I think what I'll do is maybe just copy these in a few minutes.
When was the date of this?
And that's when your grandfather... And I was going to show you another... Because this...
I don't know if I threw them my way.
You can read the, you read Spanish?
This is what they, talking about the ranches and everything.
Now, oh, this is, this is in 1931.
Yeah, that was my father, Ingeniero Jose Porres Ugarte.
He was representing my aunts, Josefina and Santiago Porres Ugarte.
But here, the other page, once you turn this way, this is what starts in St. David.
Because they were having trouble with the ones that left there to take care of them.
And that's why my father was one.
They used to have a lot of names.
I can see because my eyes go that way.
Que se encontraban ubicadas en la Colonia Fernndez Real del Distrito Galen, Estado de Chihuahua, Mxico.
Y por otra parte, por el seor Simn Parra.
He was one of the Mexicans that stayed over there.
Mayor de Edad, agricultor, vecino de la Colonia Fernndez Real, por medio del presente documento, ha concretado un contrato, un meeting, con las bases siguientes.
They agree to rent, they were going to rent to this man, Simon Parra, all the land of his property for the duration of three years.
To change from this date, recognized by Mr. Simon Parra, a fourth of all and each of the products that are obtained live concretely from all the land.
Una cuarta parte, that's what they were going to get, a fourth of everything.
That your father would be getting a fourth.
Now, why would it be just your aunts and your father wouldn't be getting anything?
And when he got married, he was, how do you say, they didn't believe when you get married, you just stay by yourself and forget about the other people.
Because my aunts didn't get married, see?
So they have that to live on.
So he was giving up any rights that he might have in the land so that they could have it.
Now, let's go back and kind of reconstruct the story.
And then he had how many brothers and sisters?
I was thinking about my grandfather, and his name was Jose Jesus Maria.
And he's the one that received the land from Refidio Diaz in 1892.
And he had how many children?
I don't remember all of them.
I know that there were two Jose's and two Josefina's.
Yes, because one died when my father was born in Mexico.
Okay, there was a Jose who died young, and then there was a Josefina.
Josefina, that's the one they're talking about here.
None of the girls married, nor the boys.
I think your father was the only one.
My father was the only one.
What did he do for a living?
Well, he used to have a charge of this hacienda.
He had a store, didn't he?
When they came here, he had a store.
But he wasn't in charge of the lands after he came here?
Well, put Maria, that she died here.
Now these people are all dead now.
The last one was my... And there was one, Josefina.
Because they put... Another, because there are two Josefinas.
Luis, now what did he do after he came to El Paso?
He had a little store, too.
That's why he didn't have those friends, because he got married.
He had a wife and kids.
And that was my, the one that I remember now, Matielita Santiago, that was the one that died.
She put up a battle for those plants.
Made a lot of, paid a lot of money out.
And she's the one that really tried the hardest to get this?
See, because they even had a, she had a cousin that was a senator in Mexico City.
And she even went to see him.
His was a cousin on your father's side or your mother's side?
Because I couldn't tell you about my...
You don't know anything about her?
I don't know anything about her.
Well, I've got one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine cousins.
There may be, but still none of them married.
And they all came to El Paso.
Now, how old was your father when he came to El Paso?
Because he was, he got married in 1917 or 1916.
I think it was 1960 because my brother was born in 1970.
Yeah, he's only a year older than I am.
I think he was about 22 or 23.
If he was born in 1881 and he came in 1910, he would have been about 31.
And he was an engineer already in Mexico.
Was he one of the older children?
He was younger than my aunt, Lita, who once died about 11 years.
So these children had not married in Mexico before 1910.
Has there ever been any talk in the family about why none of them got married?
Well, they were very strict over there in Mexico.
They didn't let her, they didn't let them go out or do this.
They were always home and growing.
I don't know what they were doing, but they were doing something.
One of them was going to get married, Matia Josefina.
In fact, she was the first, she studied over there at the first secretary for, what was that big house they have over there in Chihuahua?
My aunt used to talk about it.
But I was so small, I couldn't remember.
But she was one of the first secretary.
In fact, when she got that job, they were all going to kill her.
Or she was going to kill them, because they couldn't let a lady go out and work.
It was terrible for them, see?
But my aunt said, I'm going to work.
Well, when she started working, it continued.
Yeah, this was after they had come here to the stage.
No, that was when she was over there.
That's when she was in Chihuahua.
Because I think they studied there in Chihuahua from where they were.
From the ranchers, they sent them to Chihuahua to study.
And from there, they all came over here.
So this was your Aunt Josefina that went to work in Chihuahua in spite of her family.
Your grandmother and grandfather on your side actually lived on these ranches.
And then, do you remember how it was that they came in 1910 or 1911?
What happened in those years that made them come?
Well, I think that they knew that Pancho Villa was coming.
Why were they afraid of him?
Because my grandfather was afraid for the girls, for his daughters.
Yeah, that's what they used to tell me.
That's why there were too many.
I think there were eight or nine girls or something like that.
But the boys, I mean, why didn't the sons stay with them?
I don't know if they were or not, because with your grandfather having land given to him by Diaz, he might have been in pretty great danger in 1911, 1912.
In fact, for many years thereafter, he would have been in danger.
No, they never went back at all.
Now, when they came to El Paso, your grandfather, Jesus Maria, what did he do?
Well, I think that they put that store, a big store, that was the one that they were working all over.
And my grandfather was very old.
My grandmother, and she died over there, and she walked.
She died before... Before coming here.
And so all of the brothers and sisters, did they all live together when they got here?
In fact, my Aunt Josefina and my Tia Lita, they used to live together until they died.
Now, the boys had stores and this sort of thing, the brothers.
And the sisters, did they work at all or did they?
And the brothers worked and supported the sisters.
And none of them ever married.
But they weren't real young when they came here, were they?
Matilda, the one that died over there at the Providence Hospital.
And they didn't even know what she had, and she had appendix.
Maybe your grandfather may have been born in about 91 and been only about 20-something if he was one of the younger children.
He was born in 1881 because when they made that...
State National Bank was the same, because he used to tell me, see, that bank was made when I was born.
They were old, I'll tell you.
Then your father, what did he do after he married your mother?
He had mines here in Mexico City, Sabinal.
We used to have mines of gold, plata, and gold and everything.
But your father, after he came to El Paso, he couldn't work these mines, did he?
My father was going over, coming.
And he had a partner here, Dr. Hoffner.
He had a lot of friends.
And he used to work over in Casas Grandes and his mines.
We had, I don't know, about 10 or 15 mines.
I know that we had money.
Because I used to, they used to, we used to have three cars and chauffeurs and this and that.
But afterwards... And you lived here in El Paso?
And he kept on working as an engineer.
Now, during the first days of the revolution, what year were you born?
Was he already going back to Mexico to work in the mines?
He went all along, all through the revolution.
Was he ever in danger or anything?
My father, he used to come and go and nothing happened to him.
But he never used to go near his ranches or things, no.
He just never did go near those ranches.
He used to write like that, like that, asking for somebody would go and see about him.
Who did your grandfather leave in charge of the ranches?
Well, the ones that they have over there, the peones or...
And then he gave, I think, what I gather, he gave them power of attorney.
And all they had to do was, after the harvest, after everything was sold, they would keep part in St. Paul.
St. Paul, here to El Paso.
It was every other year they did.
After a while, they quit sending anything.
They were just complaining of having bad years.
Bad years that went after another, went after another.
They just never heard from them again.
They probably got papers on the line or something like that.
There are all kinds of things I want to ask you in a minute.
I'll go ahead with your family.
Now, your father continued going back to Mexico.
And how many children did your mother and father have?
Just tell me what they do, as you name them.
No, I think he's in computer analysis.
He's not married, and he's a computer...
Well, he was in the service.
And then there was... And then, well, in fact, it's Armida and Armando.
But I don't know what he's studying or what.
I think he's still in school.
He's the youngest, and he's not married.
And where is Armando going to college?
In the United States, I don't know where he's going.
He's a field executive for American National Insurance.
Which one of the husbands do you want?
Well, the first one, she got married over there in Mexico, see?
Did she go back to Mexico?
Oh, she used to travel a lot.
She traveled back and forth a lot.
She used to work with a lawyer, see?
But one of her trips, in her vacation trip, she met this guy in Mexico.
And he wanted to go back to Mexico, and she didn't.
He was already over there marrying, and they were living here in Los Angeles.
And then my sister said, you better go to your land and leave me alone.
Then she got married with Benny Fregoso.
And then what happened to this husband?
I don't know if it's true or not.
That's what your brother told us.
Yeah, that's what he told me.
But you don't know her third husband?
No, I don't know her third, nor her fourth.
You don't even know if she had any children.
Because she's older than I am.
I have the same thing as her grandpa, but I never use it because I don't like it.
You don't mind Jesus, but you don't like to be Maria.
All right, and you have how many children?
I better make a new page for your children.
And this tape is just about to run out.
With your children, let's see, there was one more question I think I wanted to ask.
Oh, your father and mother, how long did they, when did they die?
My mother was the one that died in 1932.
And what year did you marry?
And you met here in El Paso?
And was your father, did he remain wealthy as long as you were at home?
You said you remember being wealthy.
Well, because on account of his work.
And the three cars and everything?
Yeah, on account of his work.
My mother died, and everything went wrong for my father.
But he was always busy making maps and this and that.
Did he stop going back to Mexico after your mother died?
He still went back, but the mines just didn't work out as well.
